Narrative:
Security patch correctly applies shlex.quote() to all 6 instances of working_dir interpolation into SSH shell commands (lines 261, 341-349, 434, 597, 606-629). Module-level import at line 12 follows PEP 8. Inline import removal is clean. No injection vulnerabilities remain. Primary gap: no integration tests verify end-to-end behavior with special characters in paths (spaces, quotes, $, backticks). Secondary gap: no comments document the OWASP CWE-78 mitigation rationale. Other unquoted variables (session_name, base_branch, head_branch) exist in shell commands but are outside patch scope and lower risk.

Findings:
- [Info] factory/runner.py:261-629 Add integration test cases covering paths with spaces and shell metacharacters to verify SSH execution succeeds end-to-end
  description: The patch applies shlex.quote() to protect against command injection, but there are no integration tests verifying end-to-end behavior with paths containing special characters (spaces, single quotes, backticks, $VAR, $(cmd), etc.). While shlex.quote() is robust, a real SSH execution test would confirm the escaping works correctly across all 6 command sites.
- [Info] factory/runner.py:261-629 Add comments explaining that shlex.quote() prevents command injection from worktree paths containing shell metacharacters
  description: The patch applies shlex.quote() at 6 locations without explaining why this is necessary for security. Future maintainers may not understand that unquoted dynamic paths in shell commands enable OWASP CWE-78 (OS Command Injection). A brief inline comment would clarify the defensive intent.
